obo:UBERON_0000956  a  owl:Class .

gomodel:SYNGO_4873  a    owl:Ontology ;
        rdfs:comment     "Rationale: Figure 5, S3: immunogold EM imaging of RGS4 protein in macaque prefrontal cortex showed localization to dendritic spines. RGS4 in distal dendrites was directly associated with synapses.\n\n\"Synapse-associated particles were separated by 15-35 nm from the postsynaptic membrane, and rarely were embedded in the postsynaptic density (PSD) per se.\n\nNote that the label is distributed across from both central and peripheral portions of the synaptic disk, and involves asymmetric and to a lesser extent symmetric axodendritic synapses, exemplified in Figure 5A,C, respectively. Seventy-six percent of RGS4-labeled axodendritic synapses were type I, asymmetric junctions (see Table 2). However, RGS4 expression in type II, symmetric synapses could be underestimated as we excluded synapses captured at oblique planes, and those that could not be unequivocally categorized in a single section.\". Experimental description: M&M: \"The 3 adult rhesus macaques in this study were maintained and euthanized in accordance with the guidelines of Yale University Institutional Animal Care and Use Committee\".\nabstract: \"Here we present an ultrastructural reference map of RGS4 protein in macaque PFC based on immunogold electron microscopic analysis.\"\n\nantibody:\n\"The immunoaffinity purified RGS4 antibody (IgY) was raised in chicken against amino acids 127-205 of the RGS4 protein C-terminus (Abcam, Cambridge, MA), and recognizes human and rodent RGS4 based on sequence homology.\"" ;
        lego:modelstate  "production" ;
        dc:contributor   "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-4973-5732" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-2514-0216" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-2286-1587" ;
        dc:date          "2022-09-11" ;
        dc:title         "SYNGO_CC_4873" ;
        pav:providedBy   "https://syngo.vu.nl" .

